<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-03-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-03-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="473" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d473">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3778</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Secretary of the Navy</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Denby</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-03-28"><hi rend="italic">March 28,
                                1921</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to enclose herewith for
                            your information a copy of despatch No. 479 of January 28, 1921,<note n="18" xml:id="d473fn18">Ante, <ref target="#pg_520">p.
                                520</ref>.</note> from the American Consulate General at Shanghai
                            regarding conditions of foreign residence in the Interior of China,
                            particularly in the Yangtsze Valley.</p>
                        <pb facs="0647" n="523" xml:id="pg_523"/>
                        <p>The Department would be glad to receive an expression of opinion from you
                            as to the feasibility of arrangements for increasing the Naval forces in
                            that section of China, as is suggested in the enclosed despatch.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles E.
                            Hughes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>